default&#xa0;default(b)defaultWhat impact does the Whitehall federal defaultdepartment structuredefault defaulthave on contracting for public services that fall acrossdefault defaultdepartmental or organisational boundaries?default&#xa0;default(c)defaultHow does the Government ensure that public services developdefault defaultthe defaultright kind of leadership as they become more open, moredefault defaultsubject to scrutiny and more customer-focused?default&#xa0;default7.1.
defaultCouncils
default recognise the 
defaultimpetus
default of reduc
defaulting
default 
defaultfunding
default 
defaultand increasing demand 
defaultas being an imperative for working together
default.
default Ninety-five per cent of councils now share services, resulting in at least £278 million of efficiency savings.
default Sharing services is business as usual for councils; they are now building on that expertise to deliver more effective outcomes for local commun
defaultities by working across the public, private, and voluntary and community sector.
default 
defaultThe LGA and the National Association for Local Councils (NALC) have also produced a publication illustrating how principal and town and parish councils are working together to
default best meet the needs of their communities.
default 
default&#xa0;
default7.2.
defaultThere is nevertheless room for improvement in the way central and local government work together.
default 
defaultThe current model of local government in the context of a highly centralised national state will not serve for m
defaultuch longer. While there are some instances of more joined-up working, for example the Commissioning Academy programme or the Whitehall secondees to the community budgets areas, they are still too few. The LGA is calling for a new framework for public servi
defaultces which is able to be both strategic and locally responsive and which is supported by a more grown-up relationship between local and central government.
default&#xa0;default7.3.
defaultWhitehall’s siloed structures and at times conflicting policy objectives can mean councils find it u
defaultnnecessarily difficult to improve outcomes for local people. This has been seen, for example, in working 
defaultto reduce re-offending
default, where c
defaultouncils are regularly frustrated at a lack of engagement from some Government departments, such as the Department of Hea
defaultlth, which are failing to recognise t
defaultheir key role in reducing crime, for 
defaultexample through its funding of treatment for people with alcohol or drug addictions.
default The LGA is calling for a Crime Reduction Board that would 
defaultallow central government to replicate n
defaultationally the success achieved by councils and their partners, including the police and health services, through 
defaultthe 
defaultinnovative multi
default-agency community budget areas.
default&#xa0;
default7.4.
defaultIt is l
defaultocal government
default, through its democratically elected councillors, that is best placed to lead rewired public services. This is because they are closest to those affected by the decisions they make. A transformed and independent local government can make public services ef
defaultfective, efficient, and locally responsive. 
default&#xa0;
default7.5.
defaultThe LGA proposes that alongside a wide-ranging localisation of public services, remaining national functions be brought together into a single England Office. This would not only reduce bureaucracy and red tape
default but also remove the 
defaultartificial silos that promote duplication, waste, and conflicting policy drivers. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default8.1.
defaultThe LGA 
defaultsuppo
defaultrts councils in their ambitions to find innovative ways to deliver public services. Our Future Councils
default and Creative Councils
default programmes show how councils are taking the lead in innovative public service delivery in everything from 
defaultlooked after children and adult social care to energy supply and work readiness. 
